, England, United Kingdom":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hannah","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Antrim), English, and Scottish: variant of   Hanna  .","Americanized form of Assyrian/Chaldean   Hanna   5."],"variants":[{"name":"Hanna","meanings":["Irish (Down and Antrim) and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Ó hAnnaigh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Annach</i>’, a personal name of uncertain origin, or from Gaelic <b>Ó hÉanna</b> ‘descendant of <i>Éanna</i>’, also unexplained but well attested. See also   Hannan  . It has been suggested that the name may also derive from <i>Sheanaigh</i>, a genitive case form of the Gaelic personal name <i>Seanach</i>, but this is untenable. This was one of very few ‘Ó’ surnames to be used in Scotland, a phenomenon which was confined to the Galloway and Carrick region.","English: habitational name from Hannah (Lincolnshire), possibly derived from the Old English personal name <i>Hana</i> or Old English <i>hana</i> ‘cock’ + <i>ēg</i> ‘island’.","English: sometimes in East Anglia a variant of   Henney  ."]}]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Jane Hannah was born in 1433, in Cranworth, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married Edmund Swaithing about 1452, in Cranworth, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in 1510, in Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 77."},"et":{"1433–1510":"1433–1510","1417–1480":"1417–1480","1444–1510":"1444–1510","1433":"1433","1444":"1444","1510":"1510","1480":"1480","about 1452":"umbes 1452","1417":"1417","Letton, Norfolk, England":"Cranworth, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Letton, Herefordshire, England":"Letton, Herefordshire, England","Cranworth, Norfolk, England":"Cranworth, Norfolk, England","Cranworth, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Cranworth, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Kimberley, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1433–1510":"1433–1510","1417–1480":"1417–1480","1444–1510":"1444–1510","1433":"1433","1444":"1444","1510":"1510","1480":"1480","about 1452":"noin 1452","1417":"1417","Letton, Norfolk, England":"Cranworth, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Letton, Herefordshire, England":"Letton, Herefordshire, England","Cranworth, Norfolk, England":"Cranworth, Norfolk, England","Cranworth, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Cranworth, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Kimberley, Norfolk, England":"Kimberley, Norfolk, England","Kimberley, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Kimberley, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1433–1510":"1433–1510","1417–1480":"1417–1480","14